# Code Quality

Write modular, readable code. ESLint enforces hard limits; these rules are stricter agent guidance.

## Size limits

| Target | Limit |
|--------|-------|
| File (`.ts`/`.tsx`) | Soft 150 lines — split before growing further; hard 250 (ESLint) |
| Function | ~40 lines — extract helpers or modules |
| Nesting | Max 3 levels of `if`/`for`/`try` — use early returns and guard clauses |

## Control flow

- **3+ branches** on the same variable → `Record` lookup, `switch`, strategy map, or polymorphism
- **Same logic in 2+ places** → extract shared function/module before adding a third copy
- Prefer composition over giant conditionals

```typescript
// BAD — duplicated readiness logic across handlers
if (!databaseConnected) { throw new AppError(...); }
if (memoryPercent > 90) { throw new AppError(...); }

// GOOD — extracted predicate + single throw site
function assertReady(): void {
  if (!isDatabaseConnected()) throw readinessError('database', '...');
  if (isMemoryCritical()) throw readinessError('memory', '...');
}
```

## Agent behaviors

- Before a file passes 150 lines, stop and split — do not keep appending
- Create the right file (service, util, component) instead of inflating an existing handler
- Minimal diff — no unrelated refactors mixed with a bugfix
- Name intent; use constants for magic numbers; delete dead code and commented-out blocks
- Do not add abstractions for one-off logic
